ARTICLE
summary:      Impressionism was a 19th-century art movement originating in France in the 1860s-1870s that broke with academic painting traditions. It is characterised by visible brush strokes, open composition, emphasis on the accurate depiction of light in its changing qualities, ordinary subject matter, and the practice of painting outdoors (en plein air). The name derives from Claude Monet's painting "Impression, soleil levant" (1872).
claims:
  - The movement originated in Paris in the 1860s-1870s as a reaction against the rigid rules of academic art
  - Key characteristics include visible brush strokes, open composition, emphasis on light and its changing qualities, and ordinary subject matter
  - Artists frequently painted outdoors (en plein air) to capture natural light and colour
  - The name comes from Monet's "Impression, soleil levant" (Impression, Sunrise, 1872), used derisively by critic Louis Leroy
  - Major Impressionists include Claude Monet, Pierre-Auguste Renoir, Edgar Degas, Camille Pissarro, Alfred Sisley, and Berthe Morisot
  - The first independent Impressionist exhibition was held in 1874 at the studio of photographer Nadar
  - Impressionists used pure unmixed colours placed side by side rather than blended on the palette, relying on optical mixing
evidence:     Extensive art historical scholarship, surviving paintings in major museums worldwide (Musee d'Orsay, Metropolitan Museum of Art, National Gallery), exhibition catalogues, and contemporary art criticism
limitations:  The boundaries of the movement are debated. Some artists (Degas, Cezanne) are associated with Impressionism but diverged significantly in technique or subject matter. Post-Impressionism is a related but distinct movement.
methodology:  Encyclopedic synthesis of art history literature
---
NOTES
The Impressionists were initially rejected by the official Paris Salon and organised eight independent exhibitions between 1874 and 1886. The movement fundamentally changed the trajectory of Western art by prioritising perception over narrative. Technological advances in portable paint tubes and pre-mixed paints enabled plein air painting. Impressionism directly influenced Post-Impressionism, Fauvism, and early abstraction.